Rating: 4
TIP for using frozen scallops (or any frozen seafood - COOK IT FROZEN -- do NOT thaw, and it will hold its shape and texture. Really!) I stumbled across this looking for recipes for scallops - it sounded good and tastes even better! I've used fresh and frozen scallops and corn, and it always turns out delicious! Also be sure to use the cajun spice (great suggestion!) And degalzing with white wine makes a bit more sauce - it's so easy and SO good and really impressive to serve to guests.

Rating: 2
I used bay scallops that had been frozen and I feel this was a big mistake. Despite thawing/draining and drying, when they hit the pan they released way too much water. Sadly, my scallops never browned. I used fresh corn and cherry tomatoes. The tomatoes, also, released a bit too much moisture. Upon returning the scallops to the pan, I had a overtly mushy mixture. It tasted wonderful, but the presentation was definitely lacking. My recommendations are to use large, fresh scallops if you can get them, and to perhaps consider whole cherry tomatoes so as to reduce the chance of recreating the moisture problem I had.

